fastforward.library/--background--            fastforward.library/--background--

    PURPOSE
        fastforward.library is the Amiga multimedia engine: a runtime
        for opening, demuxing, decoding, mixing, transcoding and
        rendering audio, video, subtitle and timed-data streams.

        The architecture borrows from QuickTime (Movie / Track),
        ffmpeg (AVFormat / AVCodec / AVStream), GStreamer (Element /
        Pad / Bin) and DirectShow (Filter Graph), but the surface is
        pure Amiga - tag lists, OpenLibrary refcounting, BPTR file
        handles, exec signal masks for waiting, and realtime.library
        synchronisation for sequencer / NLE workloads.

        Two layers sit on top of one shared runtime:

           * High-level Movie API. Open a path, get tracks, set
             sinks, play. A player application fits in roughly
             30 lines of C.
           * Low-level Graph API. Create Elements, get their Pads,
             link them, drive the graph by hand. Sufficient for
             non-linear editors, transcoders, music sequencers and
             live mixers.

        Both layers share the same plugin registry, clock subsystem,
        host services and event queue.

    DESIGN PHILOSOPHY
        FastForward is named for the tape-deck metaphor and the API
        leans into it: a media stream is a tape, the engine is the
        deck, and the application drives it with the same controls a
        real-world deck has. PlayFFMovie / PauseFFMovie / StopFFMovie
        / SeekFFMovie are the literal deck buttons; the convenience
        macros RewindFFMovie, FastForwardFFMovie, ReverseFFMovie and
        ScanFFMovie compose them into one-call equivalents.

        The library is written exclusively against the Amiga ROM /
        NDK API surface for raw speed - no libc, no POSIX types. 
        Tag lists are walked through utility.library, signals replace 
        callbacks where a Wait() will do, and realtime.library drives the
        master clock when sequencers / NLEs need shared tempo
        (Conductor + Player).

    OPENING THE LIBRARY
        FastForward is opened the same way as every Amiga library:

            #include <libraries/fastforward.h>
            #include <proto/fastforward.h>

            struct Library *FastForwardBase = FF_OpenLibrary(FF_API_VERSION);
            if (FastForwardBase == NULL) {
                /* error */
            }
            LoadFFPlugins(NULL);
            ...
            UnloadFFPlugins();
            FF_CloseLibrary(FastForwardBase);

    PLUGIN DIRECTORY
        LoadFFPlugins(NULL) uses the default directory, resolved
        once at library-open time using:

            1. ENV variable  FastForward/Plugins
            2. logical assign FastForward:    (plugins live in
                                               FastForward:Plugins/)
            3. fallback       LIBS:FastForward/Plugins

    PLUGIN CONTRACT
        A FastForwarf Plugin is a LoadSeg binary that begins with 
        FFPluginHead (0x70FF4E75, id 'FFPI') and exposes one or
        more FFPlugin records. Plugin binary names use the plugin kind
        as the extension, e.g. pcm.demux, pcm.codec, file.source,
        ahi.sink.

        Plugin kinds (FFK_*) are:

            FFK_SOURCE (1)  - byte source: file, memory, URL, hook
            FFK_DEMUX  (2)  - container parser
            FFK_CODEC  (3)  - encoder / decoder
            FFK_FILTER (4)  - in-place sample / pixel filter
            FFK_SINK   (5)  - terminal output: AHI, video, callback
            FFK_MUX    (6)  - container writer
            FFK_CLOCK  (7)  - alternative clock backend

        Plugins receive an FFHost struct with allocator, logger,
        library opener, current clock pointer, event poster and
        pooled buffer allocator. Reentrancy is automatic because
        unlike shared libraries, every Open allocates a fresh instance.

    EVENTS
        Plugins post FFEvent records (format change, seek complete,
        end-of-stream, decoded metadata tags, QoS feedback, error
        reports) onto the owning Movie. The application drains them
        on its own task by waiting on the Movie's signal mask
        (GetFFMovieSignalMask) and calling PollFFMovieEvent() in a
        loop:

            FFEV_FORMAT   (1)  - format change negotiation
            FFEV_SEEK     (2)  - downstream seek completed
            FFEV_FLUSH    (3)  - discard pending data
            FFEV_EOS      (4)  - end of stream
            FFEV_TAGS     (5)  - metadata tag list available
            FFEV_QOS      (6)  - quality-of-service feedback
            FFEV_PROGRESS (7)  - buffering / transcode progress
            FFEV_NETWORK  (8)  - network state change
            FFEV_ERROR    (9)  - structured error posted to movie

    ERROR REPORTING
        Functions that can fail set a per-task error record
        retrievable via GetFFLastError(). The error codes are listed
        in <libraries/fastforward.h>; FFERR_NONE is zero. Negative
        values follow Amiga convention.

    SEE ALSO
        datatypes.library/--background--, realtime.library, 
        libraries/fastforward.h, libraries/ffplugin.h


fastforward.library/BuildFFGraphFromFileA fastforward.library/BuildFFGraphFromFileA

    NAME
        BuildFFGraphFromFileA - Auto-build a default playback graph
                                for a file. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        graph = BuildFFGraphFromFileA(path, tags);
        d0                            a0    a1

        struct FFGraph *BuildFFGraphFromFileA(CONST_STRPTR,
                                              struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Convenience for callers that want the auto-detected element
        chain for a file - typically source -> demux -> codec ->
        sink, with sinks chosen from the registry to match the
        decoded media kind (e.g. an AHI sink for an audio-only
        stream).

        After the graph returns the caller may freely rewire it:
        DisposeFFElement() the default sink and replace it with a
        callback sink for transcoding or a custom render target,
        then call RunFFGraph() to drive the assembled pipeline.

    INPUTS
        path - DOS path of the source file. Must be accessible at
               the time of the call.
        tags - Optional tag list. Forwarded to the underlying
               CreateFFGraphA() and to each element's Configure
               step; useful tags include FFE_RunMode for per-element
               execution mode and the FFSO_* source-configuration
               tags.

    RESULT
        graph - Newly created graph, or NULL on failure. Call
                GetFFLastError() for detail.

    SEE ALSO
        CreateFFGraphA(), NewFFElementA(), DisposeFFElement(),
        NewFFCallbackSinkA(), RunFFGraph(), DeleteFFGraph()


fastforward.library/BuildFFPipelineFromFile fastforward.library/BuildFFPipelineFromFile

    NAME
        BuildFFPipelineFromFile - Populate a legacy v0 pipeline
                                  from a file. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = BuildFFPipelineFromFile(pipe, path);
        d0                           a0    a1

        LONG BuildFFPipelineFromFile(struct FFPipeline *,
                                     CONST_STRPTR);

    FUNCTION
        Convenience entry point that retrofits the v0 FFPipeline
        surface with the new auto-detection logic introduced for the
        Movie / Graph API. Probes the file, selects matching demux
        and codec plugins from the registry, configures them, and
        attaches default sinks for any audio or video tracks
        encountered.

        Pipeline is the legacy alias for FFGraph. New code should
        prefer the Movie API (OpenFFMovieA) for playback and the
        Graph API (CreateFFGraphA / BuildFFGraphFromFileA) for
        editor / transcoder use; the pipeline LVOs remain available
        for binary compatibility with v0 applications.

    INPUTS
        pipe - An empty pipeline created by CreateFFPipelineA().
        path - DOS path of the source file.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success, otherwise a negative FFERR_*
             code.

    SEE ALSO
        CreateFFPipelineA(), DeleteFFPipeline(), RunFFPipeline(),
        BuildFFGraphFromFileA()


fastforward.library/CancelFFMovie         fastforward.library/CancelFFMovie

    NAME
        CancelFFMovie - Cancel a streaming or in-flight movie
                        open / play. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = CancelFFMovie(movie);
        d0                 a0

        LONG CancelFFMovie(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        Signals the player Process to abort the current open or
        playback operation and posts an FFEV_ERROR event with code
        FFERR_CANCELLED. Used to interrupt a hung network open, a
        slow HTTP source, or a long-running async preroll without
        having to wait for a timeout.

        The Movie object remains valid after the call; callers
        normally follow CancelFFMovie() with CloseFFMovie() to
        release it.

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie to cancel.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success, FFERR_NOTOPEN if the movie is
             no longer in an in-flight state.

    SEE ALSO
        OpenFFMovieA(), CloseFFMovie(), GetFFLastError()


fastforward.library/CloseFFMovie          fastforward.library/CloseFFMovie

    NAME
        CloseFFMovie - Close and dispose of a movie. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        CloseFFMovie(movie);
                     a0

        VOID CloseFFMovie(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        Tears down the playback Process, flushes all pipeline
        buffers, closes any sinks the engine created, and frees the
        movie record itself. Application-supplied sinks
        (FFMT_AudioSink / FFMT_VideoSink) are detached but NOT
        disposed - the caller retains ownership.

        Safe with NULL.

        EjectFFMovie() in <clib/fastforward_protos.h> is a macro
        alias for CloseFFMovie(), provided for symmetry with the
        tape-deck metaphor.

    INPUTS
        movie - Movie returned by OpenFFMovieA(), or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        OpenFFMovieA(), CancelFFMovie()


fastforward.library/CreateFFC2PA          fastforward.library/CreateFFC2PA

    NAME
        CreateFFC2PA - Create a chunky-to-planar render context. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        ctx = CreateFFC2PA(tags);
        d0                 a0

        struct FFC2PContext *CreateFFC2PA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Allocates a hyper-optimised chunky-to-planar render context
        bound to a destination struct BitMap. Video sinks targeting
        AGA / OCS / ECS bitmaps decode into chunky buffers in Fast
        RAM and use this helper to scatter the result into the
        Chip-RAM playfield planes for the copper, blitter or Paula
        to consume.

        The CPU backend is selected once at create time from
        SysBase->AttnFlags: 68020+ gets a register-pack path that
        skips the lookup table on the full-byte hot path; 68000 /
        68010 use the bitspread fallback. The 2 KiB bitspread table
        is built once per FastForwardBase and shared by every
        context. Plane pointers are resolved into a per-context
        cache so the hot path never walks bm->Planes[] per row.

        RTG video cards (Picasso96, CyberGraphX) have a real chunky
        framebuffer and do not need this helper; those sinks use
        FFBM_VRAM and memcpy directly.

    TAGS
        FFC2PT_BitMap        - struct BitMap *, destination.
                               Required.
        FFC2PT_MaxWidth      - UWORD, widest blit ever passed to
                               RenderFFC2P().
        FFC2PT_MaxHeight     - UWORD, tallest blit ever passed.
        FFC2PT_Depth         - ULONG, defaults to bm->Depth.
        FFC2PT_Interleaved   - BOOL, BitMap is interleaved.
        FFC2PT_AssumeAligned - BOOL, caller promises every cr_StartX
                               and cr_Width passed to RenderFFC2P()
                               is a multiple of 8. Lets the engine
                               pick the leading/trailing-free fast
                               path at create time.

    RESULT
        ctx - Opaque context, or NULL on failure. Call
              GetFFLastError() for detail.

    SEE ALSO
        RenderFFC2P(), DeleteFFC2P(), fastforward/ff_c2p.h


fastforward.library/CreateFFClockA        fastforward.library/CreateFFClockA

    NAME
        CreateFFClockA - Create a master / slave clock. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        clock = CreateFFClockA(tags);
        d0                     a0

        struct FFClock *CreateFFClockA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Allocates an FFClock backed by one of four timing sources.
        Every Graph carries a master FFClock; sequencer / NLE
        applications create their own clock and attach it via
        FFMT_Clock on OpenFFMovieA() or pass it to CreateFFGraphA().

        Clock kinds (FFCT_Kind):

            FFCK_TIMER    (1) - timer.device EUNIT_MICROHZ via
                                ReadEClock. Default. ~1us
                                resolution.
            FFCK_REALTIME (2) - realtime.library Conductor.
                                Sequencers / NLE timelines that
                                share tempo with CAMD, OctaMED,
                                Bars&Pipes.
            FFCK_AUDIO    (3) - Slaves to the audio sink's sample
                                clock. Use for A/V sync.
            FFCK_EXTERNAL (4) - Application drives SetFFClockTime()
                                itself. Mixer authoring tools.

        For FFCK_REALTIME, set FFCT_ExternalSync = TRUE to make this
        clock's Player the external sync source for its Conductor
        (FastForward becomes the timing master); leave it FALSE to
        slave to whichever third party already owns the Conductor.

    TAGS
        FFCT_Kind          - FFCK_* selecting the backend.
        FFCT_TimeScale     - Ticks per second. Default is
                             FF_TIMESCALE_USEC.
        FFCT_Conductor     - realtime.library Conductor pointer.
        FFCT_ConductorName - Look up an existing named Conductor
                             (e.g. "BarsAndPipes", "CAMD").
        FFCT_TickRate      - PPQN tick rate for Conductor mode.
        FFCT_Tempo         - BPM * 1000.
        FFCT_ExternalSync  - BOOL. TRUE: this clock's Player becomes
                             PLAYER_ExtSync source.
        FFCT_PlayerHandle  - struct Player **. Output: receives the
                             internal Player when FFCK_REALTIME.

    RESULT
        clock - Newly created clock, or NULL on failure.

    SEE ALSO
        DeleteFFClock(), StartFFClock(), StopFFClock(),
        GetFFClockTime(), SetFFClockTime(), WaitFFClock()


fastforward.library/CreateFFGraphA        fastforward.library/CreateFFGraphA

    NAME
        CreateFFGraphA - Create an empty filter graph. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        graph = CreateFFGraphA(tags);
        d0                     a0

        struct FFGraph *CreateFFGraphA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Allocates an empty FFGraph. Elements are then added via
        NewFFElementA() and wired together by name through
        GetFFElementPad() and LinkFFPads().

        Each graph owns a master clock. Pass an existing FFClock
        via tags to share timing across multiple graphs (e.g. each
        track of an NLE timeline as its own graph, all attached to
        the same FFCK_REALTIME Conductor), or omit and let the
        engine create a default FFCK_TIMER clock on first use.

        Use BuildFFGraphFromFileA() for the common case of auto-
        detecting source / demux / codec / sink for a file path.

    INPUTS
        tags - Optional tag list. May include FFMT_Clock to share
               an existing clock with another graph or movie.

    RESULT
        graph - Newly created graph, or NULL on failure.

    SEE ALSO
        DeleteFFGraph(), NewFFElementA(), LinkFFPads(),
        RunFFGraph(), BuildFFGraphFromFileA()


fastforward.library/CreateFFPipelineA     fastforward.library/CreateFFPipelineA

    NAME
        CreateFFPipelineA - Create an empty legacy v0 pipeline. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        pipe = CreateFFPipelineA(tags);
        d0                       a0

        struct FFPipeline *CreateFFPipelineA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Allocates an empty legacy v0 pipeline. FFPipeline is an
        alias for FFGraph kept for source compatibility with code
        written against the v0 API; new code should prefer
        CreateFFGraphA(). The two surfaces share the same underlying
        implementation and pipelines may be operated on with either
        Pipeline* or Graph* function families.

    INPUTS
        tags - Optional tag list. Reserved.

    RESULT
        pipe - Newly created pipeline, or NULL on failure.

    SEE ALSO
        DeleteFFPipeline(), BuildFFPipelineFromFile(),
        RunFFPipeline(), CreateFFGraphA()


fastforward.library/DecodeFFThumbnailA    fastforward.library/DecodeFFThumbnailA

    NAME
        DecodeFFThumbnailA - Decode a single frame as a preview
                             image. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        frame = DecodeFFThumbnailA(tags);
        d0                         a0

        struct FFFrameResult *DecodeFFThumbnailA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Decodes one video frame at the requested timestamp and
        returns it in an FFFrameResult. Used by file managers,
        timeline scrubbers and player UIs to render preview
        thumbnails without committing to a full playback graph.

        For still images (PNG, ILBM, JPEG, GIF) without a video
        codec plugin, the call returns NULL with FFERR_NOTSUPPORTED
        and the caller should fall back to datatypes.library.

        Animated GIFs are timed media: future gif.demux exposes
        them as a video track with frame delays in FFImageFormat.

    TAGS
        FFTH_Path        - STRPTR, source path. Mutually exclusive
                           with the other source tags.
        FFTH_FileHandle  - BPTR, open file handle. Engine takes
                           ownership.
        FFTH_MemData     - APTR, in-memory buffer.
        FFTH_MemSize     - ULONG, length of MemData.
        FFTH_Time        - ULONG, clock-unit timestamp of the
                           frame to decode. Defaults to 0.
        FFTH_Width       - ULONG, maximum width in pixels (0 = no
                           scaling).
        FFTH_Height      - ULONG, maximum height in pixels.
        FFTH_PixelFormat - ULONG, desired FFVF_* pixel format.

    RESULT
        frame - Newly allocated FFFrameResult; pass to
                FreeFFFrameResult() when done. NULL on failure.

    SEE ALSO
        FreeFFFrameResult(), ProbeFFMediaA(),
        datatypes.library/ReadDTObjectA


fastforward.library/DeleteFFC2P           fastforward.library/DeleteFFC2P

    NAME
        DeleteFFC2P - Dispose of a chunky-to-planar render
                      context. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        DeleteFFC2P(ctx);
                    a0

        VOID DeleteFFC2P(struct FFC2PContext *);

    FUNCTION
        Frees a context allocated by CreateFFC2PA(). The shared
        bitspread lookup table stays resident until the library is
        expunged. Safe with NULL.

    INPUTS
        ctx - The context to free, or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        CreateFFC2PA(), RenderFFC2P()


fastforward.library/DeleteFFClock         fastforward.library/DeleteFFClock

    NAME
        DeleteFFClock - Dispose of a clock. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        DeleteFFClock(clock);
                      a0

        VOID DeleteFFClock(struct FFClock *);

    FUNCTION
        Stops the clock if it is still running, detaches any
        realtime.library Player it owns, and frees the clock
        record. Any graphs or movies still using the clock are
        switched back to a default FFCK_TIMER clock automatically.
        Safe with NULL.

    INPUTS
        clock - Clock returned by CreateFFClockA(), or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        CreateFFClockA()


fastforward.library/DeleteFFGraph         fastforward.library/DeleteFFGraph

    NAME
        DeleteFFGraph - Dispose of a graph and all owned
                        elements. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        DeleteFFGraph(graph);
                      a0

        VOID DeleteFFGraph(struct FFGraph *);

    FUNCTION
        Calls StopFFGraph() if the graph is running, then disposes
        of every element owned by the graph (DisposeFFElement on
        each), tears down all inter-element links, and frees the
        graph record. Safe with NULL.

    INPUTS
        graph - Graph returned by CreateFFGraphA() or
                BuildFFGraphFromFileA(), or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        CreateFFGraphA(), StopFFGraph()


fastforward.library/DeleteFFPipeline      fastforward.library/DeleteFFPipeline

    NAME
        DeleteFFPipeline - Dispose of a legacy v0 pipeline. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        DeleteFFPipeline(pipe);
                         a0

        VOID DeleteFFPipeline(struct FFPipeline *);

    FUNCTION
        Alias for DeleteFFGraph() that accepts the legacy FFPipeline
        pointer type. Safe with NULL.

    INPUTS
        pipe - Pipeline returned by CreateFFPipelineA(), or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        CreateFFPipelineA(), DeleteFFGraph()


fastforward.library/DisposeFFElement      fastforward.library/DisposeFFElement

    NAME
        DisposeFFElement - Dispose of a graph element. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        DisposeFFElement(element);
                         a0

        VOID DisposeFFElement(struct FFElement *);

    FUNCTION
        Removes the element from its owning graph, unlinks every
        pad it exposes (UnlinkFFPad on each), shuts down any
        per-element Task / Process started for FFER_TASK /
        FFER_PROCESS run modes, calls the plugin's Close hook, and
        frees the element record.

        Used by editors to swap elements in and out of a graph at
        runtime - the surrounding elements remain operational and
        any new element wired in their place via LinkFFPads()
        resumes the data flow.

        Safe with NULL.

    INPUTS
        element - Element returned by NewFFElementA() /
                  NewFFCallbackSinkA(), or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        NewFFElementA(), NewFFCallbackSinkA(), UnlinkFFPad()


fastforward.library/FindFFPluginA         fastforward.library/FindFFPluginA

    NAME
        FindFFPluginA - Look up a plugin in the registry. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        plugin = FindFFPluginA(tags);
        d0                     a0

        struct FFPlugin *FindFFPluginA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Searches the registry for the first plugin matching every
        supplied tag. Use to obtain a struct FFPlugin * to feed to
        NewFFElementA(FFE_Plugin, ...) when the application wants a
        specific plugin rather than letting the engine pick.

    TAGS
        FFE_Name       - STRPTR, plugin description substring.
        FFE_Identifier - UWORD, plugin numeric id.
        FFE_Kind       - ULONG, FFK_* kind filter.
        FFE_Mime       - STRPTR, MIME type the plugin must handle.

    RESULT
        plugin - First matching plugin, or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        NextFFPlugin(), NewFFElementA(),
        LoadFFPlugins()


fastforward.library/FreeFFFrameResult     fastforward.library/FreeFFFrameResult

    NAME
        FreeFFFrameResult - Free a decoded thumbnail frame. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        FreeFFFrameResult(frame);
                          a0

        VOID FreeFFFrameResult(struct FFFrameResult *);

    FUNCTION
        Frees a frame record returned by DecodeFFThumbnailA(),
        including its fr_Data payload. Safe with NULL.

    INPUTS
        frame - Frame returned by DecodeFFThumbnailA(), or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        DecodeFFThumbnailA()


fastforward.library/FreeFFMediaInfo       fastforward.library/FreeFFMediaInfo

    NAME
        FreeFFMediaInfo - Free a probe result. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        FreeFFMediaInfo(info);
                        a0

        VOID FreeFFMediaInfo(struct FFMediaInfo *);

    FUNCTION
        Frees a probe-result record returned by ProbeFFMediaA(),
        including any duplicated strings (mi_Mime, mi_Title,
        mi_DemuxerName, mi_Path). Safe with NULL.

    INPUTS
        info - Record returned by ProbeFFMediaA(), or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        ProbeFFMediaA()


fastforward.library/GetFFClockTime        fastforward.library/GetFFClockTime

    NAME
        GetFFClockTime - Read the current clock time. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        time = GetFFClockTime(clock);
        d0                    a0

        ULONG GetFFClockTime(struct FFClock *);

    FUNCTION
        Returns the clock's current time in its configured time
        scale (FFCT_TimeScale). For FFCK_TIMER clocks this samples
        timer.device via ReadEClock; for FFCK_REALTIME the value
        comes from the underlying realtime.library Conductor; for
        FFCK_AUDIO it tracks the sink's sample counter; for
        FFCK_EXTERNAL it returns the most recent value set with
        SetFFClockTime().

        The clock advances only while it is running (StartFFClock /
        StopFFClock).

    INPUTS
        clock - The clock.

    RESULT
        time - Current time in clock-scale units.

    SEE ALSO
        SetFFClockTime(), StartFFClock(), StopFFClock(),
        WaitFFClock()


fastforward.library/GetFFElementAttrsA    fastforward.library/GetFFElementAttrsA

    NAME
        GetFFElementAttrsA - Read element attributes. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = GetFFElementAttrsA(element, tags);
        d0                      a0       a1

        LONG GetFFElementAttrsA(struct FFElement *,
                                struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Reads attributes from element into the storage pointed at
        by each TagItem's ti_Data field, in the manner of
        GetDTAttrsA(). Used both for plain capability queries
        (FFE_Kind, FFE_PadCount, FFE_Caps) and for the "stats for
        nerds" inspector tags (FFE_Description, FFE_PluginVersion,
        FFE_BuffersIn / Out, FFE_BytesIn / Out).

    TAGS
        FFE_Name          - STRPTR (out), plugin description.
        FFE_Kind          - ULONG (out), FFK_* plugin kind.
        FFE_Plugin        - struct FFPlugin * (out).
        FFE_Mime          - STRPTR (out).
        FFE_PadCount      - ULONG (out), number of pads.
        FFE_Active        - BOOL (out), TRUE while element is
                            running.
        FFE_Caps          - ULONG (out), FFC_* capability mask.
        FFE_Description   - STRPTR (out), plugin p_Description.
        FFE_PluginVersion - ULONG (out), (version<<16) | revision.
        FFE_BuffersIn     - ULONG (out), pushed-in buffer count.
        FFE_BuffersOut    - ULONG (out), pushed-out buffer count.
        FFE_BytesIn       - ULONG (out), pushed-in bytes.
        FFE_BytesOut      - ULONG (out), pushed-out bytes.

    INPUTS
        element - The element.
        tags    - Tag list whose ti_Data fields point to caller
                  storage.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        SetFFElementAttrsA(), GetFFPadAttrsA()


fastforward.library/GetFFElementPad       fastforward.library/GetFFElementPad

    NAME
        GetFFElementPad - Look up a pad on an element by name. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        pad = GetFFElementPad(element, name);
        d0                    a0       a1

        struct FFPad *GetFFElementPad(struct FFElement *,
                                      CONST_STRPTR);

    FUNCTION
        Returns the named pad on the supplied element. Pad names
        are conventional NUL-terminated strings; standard names are
        declared in <libraries/ffplugin.h>:

            FFPAD_SRC      "src"       output pad on sources /
                                       demuxers / codecs
            FFPAD_SINK     "sink"      input pad on filters /
                                       codecs / sinks / muxers
            FFPAD_AUDIO    "audio"     dedicated audio pad on
                                       demuxers / muxers
            FFPAD_VIDEO    "video"     dedicated video pad
            FFPAD_SUBTITLE "subtitle"  timed-text pad
            FFPAD_DATA     "data"      generic-data pad

        Plugins are free to expose additional named pads beyond
        these conventions (numbered audio tracks "audio0",
        "audio1", ...). GetFFElementAttrsA(FFE_PadCount) returns
        the total pad count for enumeration.

    INPUTS
        element - The element.
        name    - NUL-terminated pad name.

    RESULT
        pad - The pad, or NULL if no pad of that name exists.

    SEE ALSO
        LinkFFPads(), UnlinkFFPad(), GetFFPadAttrsA()


fastforward.library/GetFFLastError        fastforward.library/GetFFLastError

    NAME
        GetFFLastError - Retrieve structured detail for the last
                         error reported on this task. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = GetFFLastError(info);
        d0                  a0

        LONG GetFFLastError(struct FFErrorInfo *);

    FUNCTION
        Copies the most recent error record (numeric code,
        subsystem and operation tags, the originating component
        and function names, and a human-readable message) into the
        caller's FFErrorInfo. Records are kept per task, so the
        application that called the failing function is the one
        that reads the error - exactly like IoErr() on dos.library.

        Error codes (see <libraries/fastforward.h>):

            FFERR_NONE          0   - success
            FFERR_NOMEM        -1   - out of memory
            FFERR_NODEV        -2   - device unavailable
            FFERR_FORMAT       -3   - unrecognised container
            FFERR_CODEC        -4   - codec failure
            FFERR_STREAM       -5   - stream error
            FFERR_SYNC         -6   - synchronisation failure
            FFERR_BUFFER       -7   - buffer underrun / overflow
            FFERR_NOTOPEN      -8   - object not open
            FFERR_NOWINDOW     -9   - render target missing
            FFERR_HARDWARE    -10   - hardware error
            FFERR_DECODE      -11   - decoder rejected data
            FFERR_NETWORK     -12   - network failure
            FFERR_TIMEOUT     -13   - operation timed out
            FFERR_NOTSEEKABLE -14   - source cannot seek
            FFERR_CANCELLED   -15   - cancelled by caller
            FFERR_NOTFOUND    -16   - resource not found
            FFERR_NOTSUPPORTED -17  - feature unsupported

    INPUTS
        info - Storage to receive the error record.

    RESULT
        rc - The numeric error code (same as info->ei_Code).

    SEE ALSO
        libraries/fastforward.h FFERR_* constants


fastforward.library/GetFFMediaInfoAttrsA  fastforward.library/GetFFMediaInfoAttrsA

    NAME
        GetFFMediaInfoAttrsA - Read fields from a probe result. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = GetFFMediaInfoAttrsA(info, tags);
        d0                        a0    a1

        LONG GetFFMediaInfoAttrsA(struct FFMediaInfo *,
                                  struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Reads fields from a probe result returned by
        ProbeFFMediaA() into the storage pointed at by each
        TagItem's ti_Data field. Tag-based access lets callers
        request only the fields they need without committing to the
        layout of struct FFMediaInfo.

    TAGS
        FFPG_Mime         - STRPTR (out).
        FFPG_Score        - ULONG (out), 0..100 recognition score.
        FFPG_Duration     - ULONG (out), in mi_TimeScale units.
        FFPG_TrackCount   - ULONG (out).
        FFPG_HasAudio     - BOOL (out).
        FFPG_HasVideo     - BOOL (out).
        FFPG_HasSubtitle  - BOOL (out).
        FFPG_Seekable     - BOOL (out).
        FFPG_Width        - ULONG (out), pixels.
        FFPG_Height       - ULONG (out), pixels.
        FFPG_SampleRate   - ULONG (out), Hz.
        FFPG_Channels     - ULONG (out).
        FFPG_Title        - STRPTR (out).
        FFPG_DemuxerName  - STRPTR (out).

    INPUTS
        info - Result returned by ProbeFFMediaA().
        tags - Tag list whose ti_Data fields point to caller
               storage.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        ProbeFFMediaA(), FreeFFMediaInfo()


fastforward.library/GetFFMovieAttrsA      fastforward.library/GetFFMovieAttrsA

    NAME
        GetFFMovieAttrsA - Read movie attributes. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = GetFFMovieAttrsA(movie, tags);
        d0                    a0     a1

        LONG GetFFMovieAttrsA(struct FFMovie *, struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Reads attributes from movie into the storage pointed at by
        each TagItem's ti_Data field, in the manner of
        GetDTAttrsA(). Covers playback state, current timing,
        stream geometry, metadata tag lookup, and the read-only
        "stats for nerds" inspector tags.

        Metadata access uses a request / response pair: set
        FFMETA_Key to the desired key (FFMETA_Title, FFMETA_Artist,
        ...) and FFMETA_String / FFMETA_Long to point at caller
        storage for the result.

    TAGS
        FFMT_State          - ULONG (out), FFMS_*.
        FFMT_Position       - ULONG (out), clock units.
        FFMT_Duration       - ULONG (out).
        FFMT_TimeScale      - ULONG (out).
        FFMT_TrackCount     - ULONG (out).
        FFMT_Title          - STRPTR (out).
        FFMT_Mime           - STRPTR (out).
        FFMT_URL            - STRPTR (out).
        FFMT_HasAudio       - BOOL (out).
        FFMT_HasVideo       - BOOL (out).
        FFMT_HasSubtitle    - BOOL (out).
        FFMT_Seekable       - BOOL (out).
        FFMT_Width          - ULONG (out), pixels.
        FFMT_Height         - ULONG (out), pixels.
        FFMT_SampleRate     - ULONG (out), Hz.
        FFMT_Channels       - ULONG (out).
        FFMETA_Key/String/Long - tagged metadata lookup.

        Inspector / "stats for nerds":

        FFMT_PipelineSource    - struct FFElement * (out, ro).
        FFMT_PipelineDemux     - struct FFElement * (out, ro).
        FFMT_PipelineCodec     - struct FFElement * (out, ro).
        FFMT_PipelineAudioSink - struct FFElement * (out, ro).
        FFMT_PipelineVideoSink - struct FFElement * (out, ro).
        FFMT_VideoFps          - LONG (out), Q16.16 fps.
        FFMT_VideoBitrate      - ULONG (out), bits/sec.
        FFMT_AudioBitrate      - ULONG (out), bits/sec.
        FFMT_VideoFrames       - ULONG (out), decoded frames.
        FFMT_DroppedFrames     - ULONG (out), late + dropped.
        FFMT_AVDrift           - LONG (out), audio-video drift us.
        FFMT_ClockKind         - ULONG (out), FFCK_* in use.

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.
        tags  - Tag list whose ti_Data fields point to caller
                storage.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        SetFFMovieAttrsA(), GetFFTrackAttrsA(),
        GetFFElementAttrsA()


fastforward.library/GetFFMovieDuration    fastforward.library/GetFFMovieDuration

    NAME
        GetFFMovieDuration - Return total duration of a movie. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        duration = GetFFMovieDuration(movie);
        d0                            a0

        ULONG GetFFMovieDuration(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        Returns the total duration of the movie's longest track in
        the movie's FFMT_TimeScale units (typically microseconds).
        Returns 0 if the demuxer cannot determine duration (live /
        unbounded streams).

        Equivalent to GetFFMovieAttrsA(movie, FFMT_Duration, ...).

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        duration - Duration in clock units, or 0 if unknown.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFMoviePosition(), SeekFFMovie(), GetFFMovieAttrsA()


fastforward.library/GetFFMoviePosition    fastforward.library/GetFFMoviePosition

    NAME
        GetFFMoviePosition - Return current playback position. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        position = GetFFMoviePosition(movie);
        d0                            a0

        ULONG GetFFMoviePosition(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        Returns the current playhead position in the movie's
        FFMT_TimeScale units (typically microseconds). Position
        advances while the movie is in FFMS_PLAYING; pauses while
        FFMS_PAUSED; resets to 0 on stop.

        Equivalent to GetFFMovieAttrsA(movie, FFMT_Position, ...).

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        position - Current position in clock units.

    SEE ALSO
        SeekFFMovie(), GetFFMovieDuration(), GetFFMovieAttrsA()


fastforward.library/GetFFMovieSignalMask  fastforward.library/GetFFMovieSignalMask

    NAME
        GetFFMovieSignalMask - Return signal mask for waiting on a
                               movie. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        mask = GetFFMovieSignalMask(movie);
        d0                          a0

        ULONG GetFFMovieSignalMask(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        Returns a signal mask the application can pass to Wait()
        to block until the movie has new events queued, the
        playback state changes, or a track-format renegotiation
        completes. The same mask covers every kind of asynchronous
        notification the movie produces - apps drain the queue with
        PollFFMovieEvent() after Wait() returns.

        The mask combines cleanly with IDCMP masks, MIDI input
        masks, or SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C in the usual Amiga fashion:

            mask = GetFFMovieSignalMask(m);
            signals = Wait(mask | windowmask | SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C);

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        mask - Signal bit mask suitable for Wait().

    SEE ALSO
        PollFFMovieEvent(), exec.library/Wait()


fastforward.library/GetFFMovieState       fastforward.library/GetFFMovieState

    NAME
        GetFFMovieState - Return the playback state of a movie. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        state = GetFFMovieState(movie);
        d0                      a0

        ULONG GetFFMovieState(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        Returns one of:

            FFMS_STOPPED   (0) - opened but not yet started
            FFMS_OPENED    (1) - synchronous open completed
            FFMS_PREROLL   (2) - filling buffers before play
            FFMS_PLAYING   (3) - actively decoding and presenting
            FFMS_PAUSED    (4) - decoding suspended at position
            FFMS_FINISHED  (5) - reached EOS without error
            FFMS_ERROR     (6) - playback aborted; see
                                 GetFFLastError()

        State transitions also raise events
        (PollFFMovieEvent / FFEV_* records) so apps wake from
        Wait() promptly when a movie completes.

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        state - FFMS_* value.

    SEE ALSO
        PlayFFMovie(), PauseFFMovie(), StopFFMovie(),
        GetFFMovieSignalMask()


fastforward.library/GetFFPadAttrsA        fastforward.library/GetFFPadAttrsA

    NAME
        GetFFPadAttrsA - Read pad attributes. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = GetFFPadAttrsA(pad, tags);
        d0                  a0   a1

        LONG GetFFPadAttrsA(struct FFPad *, struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Reads attributes from pad into the storage pointed at by
        each TagItem's ti_Data field. Graph applications inspect
        negotiated formats before re-wiring (e.g. to confirm both
        sides of a candidate LinkFFPads() agree on sample rate or
        pixel format).

    TAGS
        FFPA_Name        - STRPTR (out), pad name.
        FFPA_Direction   - ULONG (out), FFPD_* (source / sink).
        FFPA_Linked      - BOOL (out), TRUE if peer attached.
        FFPA_Peer        - struct FFPad * (out), linked peer.
        FFPA_Caps        - ULONG (out), capability mask.
        FFPA_AudioFormat - struct FFAudioFormat * (out).
        FFPA_VideoFormat - struct FFVideoFormat * (out).
        FFPA_Index       - ULONG (out), pad index on its element.

    INPUTS
        pad  - The pad.
        tags - Tag list whose ti_Data fields point to caller
               storage.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        LinkFFPads(), GetFFElementPad()


fastforward.library/GetFFTrack            fastforward.library/GetFFTrack

    NAME
        GetFFTrack - Obtain a track by index. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        track = GetFFTrack(movie, index);
        d0                 a0     d0

        struct FFTrack *GetFFTrack(struct FFMovie *, ULONG);

    FUNCTION
        Returns the FFTrack at the supplied zero-based index. Track
        ordering matches the demuxer's view of the source file;
        track count is available via GetFFTrackCount() or
        GetFFMovieAttrsA(FFMT_TrackCount).

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.
        index - Zero-based track index (0..GetFFTrackCount()-1).

    RESULT
        track - The track, or NULL if index is out of range.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFTrackCount(), GetFFTrackAttrsA(), SetFFTrackAttrsA()


fastforward.library/GetFFTrackAttrsA      fastforward.library/GetFFTrackAttrsA

    NAME
        GetFFTrackAttrsA - Read track attributes. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = GetFFTrackAttrsA(track, tags);
        d0                    a0     a1

        LONG GetFFTrackAttrsA(struct FFTrack *, struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Reads attributes from track into the storage pointed at by
        each TagItem's ti_Data field. Used to query track kind,
        codec, geometry, language and the per-track sink / source
        elements bound by the engine.

    TAGS
        FFTA_Index       - ULONG (out).
        FFTA_Kind        - ULONG (out), FFTK_AUDIO / FFTK_VIDEO /
                           FFTK_DATA / FFTK_MIDI / FFTK_SUBTITLE.
        FFTA_Description - STRPTR (out).
        FFTA_Enabled     - BOOL.
        FFTA_Volume      - ULONG, 0..0x10000.
        FFTA_Mute        - BOOL.
        FFTA_AudioFormat - struct FFAudioFormat * (out).
        FFTA_VideoFormat - struct FFVideoFormat * (out).
        FFTA_Sink        - struct FFElement * (out).
        FFTA_Source      - struct FFElement * (out).
        FFTA_Duration    - ULONG (out).
        FFTA_Language    - STRPTR (out), ISO 639.
        FFTA_CodecName   - STRPTR (out).
        FFTA_BitRate     - ULONG (out), bits/sec.
        FFTA_Default     - BOOL (out), default track flag.
        FFTA_Seekable    - BOOL (out).

    INPUTS
        track - The track.
        tags  - Tag list whose ti_Data fields point to caller
                storage.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        SetFFTrackAttrsA(), GetFFTrack()


fastforward.library/GetFFTrackCount       fastforward.library/GetFFTrackCount

    NAME
        GetFFTrackCount - Return the number of tracks in a
                          movie. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        count = GetFFTrackCount(movie);
        d0                      a0

        ULONG GetFFTrackCount(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        Returns the number of independent tracks the demuxer
        identified in the source. Equivalent to
        GetFFMovieAttrsA(movie, FFMT_TrackCount, ...).

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        count - Number of tracks (>= 0).

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFTrack(), GetFFMovieAttrsA()


fastforward.library/LinkFFPads            fastforward.library/LinkFFPads

    NAME
        LinkFFPads - Connect a source pad to a sink pad. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = LinkFFPads(src, dst);
        d0              a0   a1

        LONG LinkFFPads(struct FFPad *, struct FFPad *);

    FUNCTION
        Connects an output pad (FFPD_SRC) to an input pad
        (FFPD_SINK). The engine negotiates format compatibility
        between the two pads' caps masks and refuses the link if no
        common format is reachable.

        For inline (FFER_INLINE) elements the link is a direct
        function-pointer attachment; for FFER_TASK / FFER_PROCESS
        elements it allocates per-link message ports and an
        FFE_PoolDepth-deep buffer ring through which producer and
        consumer hand buffers.

        UnlinkFFPad() reverses the operation.

    INPUTS
        src - Source pad (output).
        dst - Sink pad (input).

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success; FFERR_FORMAT if no compatible
             format negotiation succeeded.

    SEE ALSO
        UnlinkFFPad(), GetFFElementPad(), GetFFPadAttrsA()


fastforward.library/LoadFFPlugins         fastforward.library/LoadFFPlugins

    NAME
        LoadFFPlugins - Scan a directory and register plugins
                        found there. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        count = LoadFFPlugins(dir);
        d0                    a0

        LONG LoadFFPlugins(CONST_STRPTR);

    FUNCTION
        Walks the supplied directory, LoadSeg()'s every file whose
        contents begin with FFPluginHead (security word
        0x70FF4E75, id 'FFPI'), and registers every FFPlugin record
        the binary exposes with the engine's runtime registry.
        Built-in plugins (file source, PCM demux, PCM codec, AHI
        sink, callback sink, memory source) are registered
        unconditionally and need no on-disk binary.

        Pass NULL to use the default directory, resolved once at
        library-open time via (in order):

            1. ENV variable  FastForward/Plugins
            2. logical assign FastForward:    (plugins live in
                                               FastForward:Plugins/)
            3. fallback       LIBS:FastForward/Plugins

        Applications can override the default by passing an
        explicit path - useful for transcoders / editors that ship
        a private plugin bundle.

        UnloadFFPlugins() reverses the operation.

    INPUTS
        dir - DOS path of the plugin directory, or NULL for the
              default location.

    RESULT
        count - Number of plugins registered, or a negative
                FFERR_* on failure.

    SEE ALSO
        UnloadFFPlugins(), FindFFPluginA(), NextFFPlugin(),
        SetFFLogLevel()


fastforward.library/NewFFCallbackSinkA    fastforward.library/NewFFCallbackSinkA

    NAME
        NewFFCallbackSinkA - Create a callback-driven sink
                             element. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        sink = NewFFCallbackSinkA(graph, cb, tags);
        d0                        a0     a1  a2

        struct FFElement *NewFFCallbackSinkA(struct FFGraph *,
                                             struct FFCallbacks *,
                                             struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Allocates a built-in sink element that delivers decoded
        audio / video / subtitle blocks to caller-supplied
        function pointers in a struct FFCallbacks. Used to render
        inside an application widget without writing a full plugin:
        WritePixelArray() into a custom window, push samples into
        a waveform display, write packets to a transcoder's output
        mux, etc.

        Callbacks run on the player Process. Heavy work that needs
        Intuition or DOS context should be deferred onto the
        application's main task via a message port.

        Wire the callback sink as the audio or video sink of a
        Movie by passing it to OpenFFMovieA(FFMT_AudioSink, ...) or
        FFMT_VideoSink. In Graph mode, link the sink's "sink" pad
        to whichever element produces the desired buffers.

    INPUTS
        graph - Owning graph.
        cb    - Caller-allocated FFCallbacks. Members:
                  cb_OnFormat   - format negotiation
                  cb_OnAudio    - decoded PCM buffer
                  cb_OnVideo    - decoded video frame
                  cb_OnSubtitle - decoded subtitle cue
                  cb_OnEvent    - upstream control event
                  cb_UserData   - opaque pointer passed back
        tags  - Optional tags; reserved for future expansion.

    RESULT
        sink - The new element, or NULL on failure.

    SEE ALSO
        NewFFElementA(), DisposeFFElement(),
        OpenFFMovieA() (FFMT_AudioSink / FFMT_VideoSink)


fastforward.library/NewFFElementA         fastforward.library/NewFFElementA

    NAME
        NewFFElementA - Create a graph element. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        element = NewFFElementA(graph, tags);
        d0                      a0     a1

        struct FFElement *NewFFElementA(struct FFGraph *,
                                        struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Creates an FFElement bound to a registered plugin and adds
        it to the supplied graph. Plugin selection is driven by
        tags: name, identifier, kind, MIME, or explicit FFPlugin
        pointer. The engine instantiates the plugin via its Open
        hook and links the element into the graph's element list.

        By default elements run in FFER_INLINE mode on the calling
        task. Pass FFE_RunMode = FFER_TASK or FFER_PROCESS to give
        the element its own Exec Task / DOS Process; pads then
        communicate via Exec Messages on a per-link pool. Use
        FFE_SyncToConductor on a producer element to attach a
        realtime.library Player to the graph's master Conductor.

    TAGS
        FFE_Name            - STRPTR, plugin description match.
        FFE_Identifier      - UWORD, plugin numeric id.
        FFE_Kind            - ULONG, FFK_* (SOURCE, DEMUX, CODEC,
                              FILTER, SINK, MUX, CLOCK).
        FFE_Plugin          - struct FFPlugin *, explicit plugin.
        FFE_Mime            - STRPTR, MIME the plugin must handle.
        FFE_Callbacks       - struct FFCallbacks *.
        FFE_UserData        - APTR, caller cookie.
        FFE_NoAutoConfigure - BOOL, skip default configuration.
        FFE_RunMode         - ULONG, FFER_INLINE / FFER_TASK /
                              FFER_PROCESS.
        FFE_TaskPriority    - BYTE, -128..+127 for FFER_TASK /
                              FFER_PROCESS.
        FFE_StackSize       - ULONG, bytes; default 8192.
        FFE_SyncToConductor - BOOL, attach Player to graph's
                              Conductor.
        FFE_PoolDepth       - ULONG, buffers per output link;
                              default 4.

    INPUTS
        graph - Owning graph.
        tags  - Tag list - see TAGS.

    RESULT
        element - The new element, or NULL on failure.

    SEE ALSO
        DisposeFFElement(), NewFFCallbackSinkA(),
        GetFFElementPad(), SetFFElementAttrsA(),
        BuildFFGraphFromFileA()


fastforward.library/NextFFPlugin          fastforward.library/NextFFPlugin

    NAME
        NextFFPlugin - Iterate the registered plugin list. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        plugin = NextFFPlugin(prev);
        d0                    a0

        struct FFPlugin *NextFFPlugin(struct FFPlugin *);

    FUNCTION
        Returns the next registered plugin after prev. Pass NULL
        for prev to obtain the first plugin. The iteration order
        is registration order; the registry is locked for the
        duration of the call so it is safe to call from one task
        while another task loads / unloads plugins.

        Typical use:

            struct FFPlugin *p = NULL;
            while ((p = NextFFPlugin(p)) != NULL) {
                /* inspect p->p_Description, p->p_Kind, etc. */
            }

    INPUTS
        prev - Plugin returned by a previous call, or NULL to
               start.

    RESULT
        plugin - Next plugin, or NULL at end-of-list.

    SEE ALSO
        FindFFPluginA(), LoadFFPlugins(), libraries/ffplugin.h


fastforward.library/OpenFFMovieA          fastforward.library/OpenFFMovieA

    NAME
        OpenFFMovieA - Open a movie from a path, URL, memory
                       buffer or callback. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        movie = OpenFFMovieA(tags);
        d0                   a0

        struct FFMovie *OpenFFMovieA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Opens a media source described by tags, probes it to
        identify container and codecs, builds the default playback
        graph (source -> demux -> codec(s) -> sink(s)) and returns
        a Movie handle ready for transport. Set FFMT_AutoPlay =
        TRUE to spawn the player Process and begin playback
        immediately; otherwise the Movie is in FFMS_OPENED until
        the application calls PlayFFMovie().

        Sources accepted (mutually exclusive):

            FFMT_Path        - DOS file path
            FFMT_FileHandle  - BPTR; engine takes ownership
            FFMT_URL         - network location (http/rtsp/hls;
                               requires network source plugin)
            FFMT_MemData +
            FFMT_MemSize     - in-memory buffer
            FFMT_IOCallbacks +
            FFMT_IOUserData  - application-supplied byte stream

        Audio / video output may be redirected by supplying
        FFMT_AudioSink / FFMT_VideoSink (struct FFElement *
        returned by NewFFCallbackSinkA() or NewFFElementA()), or by
        passing render-target hints (FFMT_Window, FFMT_Screen,
        FFMT_RastPort, FFMT_BitMap) that the engine routes to
        whichever video sink ends up plumbed for the stream.

    TAGS
        FFMT_Path / FFMT_FileHandle / FFMT_URL / FFMT_MemData /
        FFMT_MemSize / FFMT_IOCallbacks / FFMT_IOUserData
            - Source selection (mutually exclusive).
        FFMT_AutoPlay      - BOOL, start playback immediately.
        FFMT_AudioSink     - struct FFElement *, app-supplied
                             audio sink.
        FFMT_VideoSink     - struct FFElement *, app-supplied
                             video sink.
        FFMT_AHIUnit       - ULONG, AHI device unit for default
                             audio sink.
        FFMT_Volume        - ULONG, 0..0x10000.
        FFMT_Loop          - BOOL, loop on EOS.
        FFMT_StartTime     - ULONG, start position in clock units.
        FFMT_Clock         - struct FFClock *, external master
                             clock.
        FFMT_TimeScale     - ULONG, ticks per second.
        FFMT_Window/Screen/
        RastPort/BitMap    - render-target hints (video).
        FFMT_DestX / DestY -
        DestWidth / DestHeight - destination rectangle.
        FFMT_PlayRate      - LONG, signed Q16.16 transport rate.
        FFMT_LoopMode      - ULONG, FFLM_OFF / FFLM_LOOP /
                             FFLM_PINGPONG / FFLM_REGION.
        FFMT_LoopStart /
        FFMT_LoopEnd       - ULONG, region-loop boundaries.
        FFMT_Timeout       - ULONG, ms, for network sources.
        FFMT_UserAgent     - STRPTR, for HTTP sources.
        FFMT_ProxyServer /
        FFMT_ProxyPort     - HTTP proxy.
        FFMT_AsyncOpen     - BOOL, non-blocking open.
        FFMT_OpenSignal    - ULONG, signal bit raised when an
                             async open completes.
        FFMT_CancelSignal  - ULONG, signal bit observed for
                             user-driven abort.

    RESULT
        movie - The new movie, or NULL on failure. Call
                GetFFLastError() for detail.

    SEE ALSO
        CloseFFMovie(), PlayFFMovie(), PauseFFMovie(),
        StopFFMovie(), SeekFFMovie(), GetFFMovieSignalMask(),
        PollFFMovieEvent(), NewFFCallbackSinkA(), CancelFFMovie()


fastforward.library/PauseFFMovie          fastforward.library/PauseFFMovie

    NAME
        PauseFFMovie - Suspend playback at the current position. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = PauseFFMovie(movie);
        d0                a0

        LONG PauseFFMovie(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        The Pause deck button. Stops the clock and freezes every
        running element at its current position. Buffer pools and
        decoded frames are preserved so PlayFFMovie() resumes
        immediately without re-decoding.

        Equivalent to SetFFMovieAttrsA(movie, FFMT_PlayRate,
        FF_RATE_PAUSE, TAG_DONE), but cheaper because the engine
        knows to bypass any rate-change negotiation.

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        PlayFFMovie(), StopFFMovie(), SeekFFMovie(),
        SetFFMovieAttrsA() (FFMT_PlayRate)


fastforward.library/PlayFFMovie           fastforward.library/PlayFFMovie

    NAME
        PlayFFMovie - Begin or resume playback. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = PlayFFMovie(movie);
        d0               a0

        LONG PlayFFMovie(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        The Play deck button. Spawns (or resumes) the player
        Process, starts the clock, and pushes the movie into the
        FFMS_PLAYING state. Returns immediately - playback runs
        asynchronously and the application waits on the movie's
        signal mask for event notifications.

        After preroll the engine transitions FFMS_PREROLL ->
        FFMS_PLAYING. When the source reaches end-of-stream the
        movie transitions to FFMS_FINISHED and posts an FFEV_EOS
        event; with FFMT_Loop = TRUE it seeks back to the start
        instead.

        ResumeFFMovie() in <clib/fastforward_protos.h> is a macro
        alias provided for symmetry with the tape-deck metaphor.

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        PauseFFMovie(), StopFFMovie(), SeekFFMovie(),
        GetFFMovieSignalMask()


fastforward.library/PollFFMovieEvent      fastforward.library/PollFFMovieEvent

    NAME
        PollFFMovieEvent - Drain one event from a movie's queue. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = PollFFMovieEvent(movie, event);
        d0                    a0     a1

        LONG PollFFMovieEvent(struct FFMovie *, struct FFEvent *);

    FUNCTION
        Copies one pending event from the movie's event queue into
        the caller-supplied FFEvent and removes it from the queue.
        Returns > 0 when an event was returned, 0 when the queue
        is empty, and a negative FFERR_* on error.

        Applications drain the queue in a tight loop after Wait()
        returns the movie's signal mask:

            mask = GetFFMovieSignalMask(m);
            signals = Wait(mask | mywin | SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C);
            while (PollFFMovieEvent(m, &ev) > 0) {
                switch (ev.fe_Kind) {
                case FFEV_EOS:    ...
                case FFEV_FORMAT: ...
                case FFEV_SEEK:   ...
                case FFEV_TAGS:   ...
                case FFEV_QOS:    ...
                case FFEV_ERROR:  ...
                }
            }

        Event payloads are attached to the FFEvent record in
        kind-specific fields (see <libraries/ffplugin.h>).

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.
        event - Storage to receive one event.

    RESULT
        rc - 1 if an event was returned, 0 if the queue is empty,
             negative on error.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFMovieSignalMask(), libraries/ffplugin.h FFEV_*


fastforward.library/ProbeFFMediaA         fastforward.library/ProbeFFMediaA

    NAME
        ProbeFFMediaA - Identify a media source without building
                        a playback graph. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        info = ProbeFFMediaA(tags);
        d0                   a0

        struct FFMediaInfo *ProbeFFMediaA(struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Identifies the container / codec / track layout of a media
        source without committing to a full playback graph. Used
        by file managers, browsers, file requesters and import
        wizards to populate "details" panes from a fast header
        sniff (FFREC_LIGHT) or a brief demuxer open
        (FFREC_HEAVY) that also returns duration when
        p_QueryDuration is available.

        The returned FFMediaInfo must be freed with
        FreeFFMediaInfo(). Individual fields are also reachable
        via GetFFMediaInfoAttrsA() for callers that prefer tagged
        access.

    TAGS
        FFPG_Path        - STRPTR, local file path.
        FFPG_FileHandle  - BPTR, open file handle.
        FFPG_URL         - STRPTR, http/rtsp/hls location.
        FFPG_MemData     - APTR, in-memory header bytes.
        FFPG_MemSize     - ULONG, length of MemData.
        FFPG_Recognition - ULONG, FFREC_LIGHT (header only) or
                           FFREC_HEAVY (open demuxer briefly).
        FFPG_MediaTypes  - ULONG, FFTK_* mask to filter results.

    RESULT
        info - Newly allocated probe record, or NULL.

    SEE ALSO
        FreeFFMediaInfo(), GetFFMediaInfoAttrsA(),
        DecodeFFThumbnailA()


fastforward.library/RenderFFC2P           fastforward.library/RenderFFC2P

    NAME
        RenderFFC2P - Blit one chunky rectangle into the bound
                      bitmap. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = RenderFFC2P(ctx, req);
        d0               a0   a1

        LONG RenderFFC2P(struct FFC2PContext *,
                         struct FFC2PRequest *);

    FUNCTION
        Translates the chunky rectangle described by req
        (cr_StartX, cr_StartY, cr_Width, cr_Height, cr_SrcModulo)
        into the planar bitmap bound at CreateFFC2PA() time. The
        backend selected at create time (register-pack on 68020+,
        bitspread on 68000/68010) processes the full-byte body in
        the hot loop; leading and trailing partial-byte edges
        always use the bitspread table.

        Per-call flags (cr_Flags):

            FFC2PF_NO_TRAILING_RMW - skip read-modify-write on the
                                     right edge (full-width
                                     overwrite, the common case).
            FFC2PF_NO_LEADING_RMW  - same for the left edge.
            FFC2PF_REENTRANT       - caller promises this context
                                     is only ever touched by the
                                     calling task; engine skips
                                     the Forbid() it would
                                     otherwise wrap around the
                                     cached plane-pointer array.

        Return codes:

            FFC2P_OK              0
            FFC2P_BAD_REQUEST    -1   - NULL pointer / zero size
            FFC2P_OUT_OF_RANGE   -2   - rectangle escapes BitMap
            FFC2P_NOT_IMPLEMENTED -3  - reserved

        Reentrant per context: serialise calls if the same context
        is shared between tasks (typical sinks bind a context to
        one task and never share, avoiding any locking).

    INPUTS
        ctx - Context from CreateFFC2PA().
        req - Populated FFC2PRequest.

    RESULT
        rc - FFC2P_OK or a negative FFC2P_* status.

    SEE ALSO
        CreateFFC2PA(), DeleteFFC2P(), fastforward/ff_c2p.h


fastforward.library/RunFFGraph            fastforward.library/RunFFGraph

    NAME
        RunFFGraph - Start a graph running. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = RunFFGraph(graph);
        d0              a0

        LONG RunFFGraph(struct FFGraph *);

    FUNCTION
        Walks the graph's element list, starts a Task for every
        element whose FFE_RunMode is non-INLINE, allocates
        per-element message ports (fe_InPort) and per-link buffer
        pools (fe_BufferPool), and - for any element that asked
        for FFE_SyncToConductor - creates a Player attached to the
        graph's Conductor. Starts the graph's master clock and
        kicks the source elements to begin producing data.

        Returns once all tasks are spawned and the graph is
        running; data flow continues asynchronously until
        StopFFGraph(), an EOS, or a fatal error.

    INPUTS
        graph - Graph returned by CreateFFGraphA() /
                BuildFFGraphFromFileA().

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        StopFFGraph(), DeleteFFGraph(), CreateFFGraphA()


fastforward.library/RunFFPipeline         fastforward.library/RunFFPipeline

    NAME
        RunFFPipeline - Start a legacy v0 pipeline. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = RunFFPipeline(pipe);
        d0                 a0

        LONG RunFFPipeline(struct FFPipeline *);

    FUNCTION
        Legacy v0 alias for RunFFGraph(). Accepts the FFPipeline
        pointer type returned by CreateFFPipelineA() /
        BuildFFPipelineFromFile().

    INPUTS
        pipe - The pipeline.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        StopFFPipeline(), RunFFGraph()


fastforward.library/SeekFFMovie           fastforward.library/SeekFFMovie

    NAME
        SeekFFMovie - Seek to an absolute timestamp. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = SeekFFMovie(movie, time, flags);
        d0               a0     d0    d1

        LONG SeekFFMovie(struct FFMovie *, ULONG, ULONG);

    FUNCTION
        Seeks the movie to the supplied absolute timestamp in the
        movie's FFMT_TimeScale units. The demuxer chooses the
        nearest keyframe at or before time; flags refine the
        target:

            FFCF_FLUSH    - discard pending buffers before seeking
            FFCF_KEYFRAME - snap to the nearest keyframe
            FFCF_BACKWARD - prefer seeking backwards over forwards
            FFCF_ACCURATE - decode forward from keyframe to land
                            on the exact requested frame

        Returns immediately; the seek runs asynchronously and an
        FFEV_SEEK event is posted on completion. Applications that
        need synchronous behaviour wait on GetFFMovieSignalMask().

        Sources that cannot seek (live streams, callback streams
        without io_Seek) return FFERR_NOTSEEKABLE.

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.
        time  - Target time in clock units.
        flags - Combination of FFCF_* flags.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFMoviePosition(), GetFFMovieDuration(),
        PauseFFMovie(), PollFFMovieEvent()


fastforward.library/SetFFClockTime        fastforward.library/SetFFClockTime

    NAME
        SetFFClockTime - Set the current clock time. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = SetFFClockTime(clock, time);
        d0                  a0     d0

        LONG SetFFClockTime(struct FFClock *, ULONG);

    FUNCTION
        Sets the clock's current time in its configured time scale
        (FFCT_TimeScale). For FFCK_EXTERNAL clocks this is the
        usual entry point - the application drives the clock by
        repeatedly calling SetFFClockTime() and elements bound to
        the clock observe the change at the next tick boundary.

        For FFCK_REALTIME, SetFFClockTime() defers to
        SetConductorState() on the underlying realtime.library
        Conductor; for FFCK_TIMER and FFCK_AUDIO the operation
        applies an offset relative to the underlying time source.

    INPUTS
        clock - The clock.
        time  - New time value in clock-scale units.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFClockTime(), CreateFFClockA()


fastforward.library/SetFFElementAttrsA    fastforward.library/SetFFElementAttrsA

    NAME
        SetFFElementAttrsA - Set element attributes. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = SetFFElementAttrsA(element, tags);
        d0                      a0       a1

        LONG SetFFElementAttrsA(struct FFElement *,
                                struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Sets attributes on element. Tags cover both engine-level
        properties (FFE_RunMode / FFE_TaskPriority / FFE_StackSize
        / FFE_SyncToConductor / FFE_PoolDepth) and plugin-specific
        configuration forwarded to the plugin's Configure hook
        (e.g. FFSO_URL / FFSO_MemData on a source, AHI unit /
        volume on an audio sink, encoder bitrate on an encoder).

        Most engine-level properties must be set before the
        containing graph is started; plugin-specific properties
        may be changed at runtime when the plugin advertises
        FFC_REENTRANT.

    INPUTS
        element - The element.
        tags    - Tag list of attributes to set.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFElementAttrsA(), NewFFElementA()


fastforward.library/SetFFLogLevel         fastforward.library/SetFFLogLevel

    NAME
        SetFFLogLevel - Set the global library log level. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        SetFFLogLevel(level);
                      d0

        VOID SetFFLogLevel(ULONG);

    FUNCTION
        Sets the threshold below which log messages are silently
        dropped. Default is FFLOG_WARN. Plugins and engine code
        call host->fh_Log() to emit messages; the engine compares
        the supplied level against the global threshold and only
        formats / writes messages at or above it.

        Levels:

            FFLOG_NONE  (0) - silence
            FFLOG_ERROR (1) - structured error reports only
            FFLOG_WARN  (2) - warnings and errors
            FFLOG_INFO  (3) - additional informational notices
            FFLOG_DEBUG (4) - verbose internal traces

        Library log output is routed to stdout when the library
        was opened from a CLI context, and otherwise discarded;
        future revisions may route through a system-wide log
        device.

    INPUTS
        level - FFLOG_* threshold.

    SEE ALSO
        libraries/fastforward.h FFLOG_* constants


fastforward.library/SetFFMovieAttrsA      fastforward.library/SetFFMovieAttrsA

    NAME
        SetFFMovieAttrsA - Set movie attributes. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = SetFFMovieAttrsA(movie, tags);
        d0                    a0     a1

        LONG SetFFMovieAttrsA(struct FFMovie *, struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Sets attributes on movie. The same tag set OpenFFMovieA()
        accepts is honoured here for runtime mutations: change
        volume, swap audio / video sinks, set transport rate and
        loop mode, attach an external clock, retarget a video
        sink to a different RastPort, etc.

        Read-only tags (FFMT_State, FFMT_Position, FFMT_Duration,
        FFMT_TrackCount, the FFMT_Pipeline* inspector tags) are
        rejected with FFERR_NOTSUPPORTED.

        The tape-deck convenience macros (FastForwardFFMovie,
        ReverseFFMovie, ScanFFMovie, RewindFFMovie) in
        <clib/fastforward_protos.h> are thin wrappers around
        SetFFMovieAttrsA(movie, FFMT_PlayRate, ...).

    TAGS
        FFMT_AutoPlay / FFMT_Volume / FFMT_Loop / FFMT_LoopMode /
        FFMT_LoopStart / FFMT_LoopEnd / FFMT_PlayRate /
        FFMT_StartTime / FFMT_AudioSink / FFMT_VideoSink /
        FFMT_AHIUnit / FFMT_Clock / FFMT_Window / FFMT_Screen /
        FFMT_RastPort / FFMT_BitMap / FFMT_DestX / FFMT_DestY /
        FFMT_DestWidth / FFMT_DestHeight / FFMT_Timeout /
        FFMT_UserAgent / FFMT_ProxyServer / FFMT_ProxyPort /
        FFMT_CancelSignal / FFMT_OpenSignal - see OpenFFMovieA().

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.
        tags  - Tag list of attributes to set.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFMovieAttrsA(), OpenFFMovieA()


fastforward.library/SetFFTrackAttrsA      fastforward.library/SetFFTrackAttrsA

    NAME
        SetFFTrackAttrsA - Set track attributes. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = SetFFTrackAttrsA(track, tags);
        d0                    a0     a1

        LONG SetFFTrackAttrsA(struct FFTrack *, struct TagItem *);

    FUNCTION
        Sets attributes on track. Common runtime mutations are
        enable / disable for solo / mute behaviour, per-track
        volume scaling, swap of the per-track sink for a custom
        callback sink, and language selection on multilingual
        sources.

        Read-only attributes (FFTA_Index, FFTA_Kind,
        FFTA_AudioFormat, FFTA_VideoFormat, FFTA_Duration,
        FFTA_CodecName, FFTA_BitRate, FFTA_Default, FFTA_Seekable)
        are rejected with FFERR_NOTSUPPORTED.

    TAGS
        FFTA_Enabled    - BOOL.
        FFTA_Volume     - ULONG, 0..0x10000.
        FFTA_Mute       - BOOL.
        FFTA_Sink       - struct FFElement *.
        FFTA_Source     - struct FFElement *.
        FFTA_Language   - STRPTR, ISO 639.
        FFTA_Description - STRPTR.

    INPUTS
        track - The track.
        tags  - Tag list of attributes to set.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFTrackAttrsA(), GetFFTrack()


fastforward.library/StartFFClock          fastforward.library/StartFFClock

    NAME
        StartFFClock - Start a clock advancing. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = StartFFClock(clock);
        d0                a0

        LONG StartFFClock(struct FFClock *);

    FUNCTION
        Starts the clock running. After StartFFClock() the clock
        advances at its configured tick rate; GetFFClockTime()
        returns increasing values; tasks blocked in WaitFFClock()
        wake when their target time is reached.

        For FFCK_REALTIME this attaches the underlying Player to
        its Conductor; for FFCK_TIMER it samples the current EClock
        as the zero reference; for FFCK_AUDIO it begins tracking
        the sink's sample counter; for FFCK_EXTERNAL it permits
        WaitFFClock() to proceed (the clock still only advances
        via SetFFClockTime()).

    INPUTS
        clock - The clock.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        StopFFClock(), CreateFFClockA(), WaitFFClock()


fastforward.library/StopFFClock           fastforward.library/StopFFClock

    NAME
        StopFFClock - Stop a clock. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = StopFFClock(clock);
        d0               a0

        LONG StopFFClock(struct FFClock *);

    FUNCTION
        Stops the clock. After StopFFClock() the clock no longer
        advances; tasks blocked in WaitFFClock() return promptly
        with the clock's last value. Repeated calls are safe.

    INPUTS
        clock - The clock.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        StartFFClock(), CreateFFClockA()


fastforward.library/StopFFGraph           fastforward.library/StopFFGraph

    NAME
        StopFFGraph - Stop a running graph. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        StopFFGraph(graph);
                    a0

        VOID StopFFGraph(struct FFGraph *);

    FUNCTION
        Signals every running task in the graph (FFER_TASK /
        FFER_PROCESS elements) to exit, flushes all in-flight
        buffers, stops the graph's master clock, and tears the
        per-link plumbing down. Safe to call from a signal
        handler or another task; the call blocks until every task
        has reported exit.

        The graph itself remains valid - call RunFFGraph() again
        to restart it, or DeleteFFGraph() to dispose of it.

    INPUTS
        graph - The graph.

    SEE ALSO
        RunFFGraph(), DeleteFFGraph()


fastforward.library/StopFFMovie           fastforward.library/StopFFMovie

    NAME
        StopFFMovie - Stop playback and reset to the start. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = StopFFMovie(movie);
        d0               a0

        LONG StopFFMovie(struct FFMovie *);

    FUNCTION
        The Stop deck button. Halts playback, flushes all decoded
        buffers, and resets the playhead to position 0. The movie
        transitions to FFMS_STOPPED; a subsequent PlayFFMovie()
        starts from the beginning.

        Use PauseFFMovie() to suspend playback without losing
        position. Use RewindFFMovie() in
        <clib/fastforward_protos.h> for the explicit "stop and
        seek to head" behaviour expressed as one call.

    INPUTS
        movie - The movie.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        PlayFFMovie(), PauseFFMovie(), SeekFFMovie(),
        CloseFFMovie()


fastforward.library/StopFFPipeline        fastforward.library/StopFFPipeline

    NAME
        StopFFPipeline - Stop a running legacy v0 pipeline. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        StopFFPipeline(pipe);
                       a0

        VOID StopFFPipeline(struct FFPipeline *);

    FUNCTION
        Legacy v0 alias for StopFFGraph(). Accepts the FFPipeline
        pointer type returned by CreateFFPipelineA() /
        BuildFFPipelineFromFile().

    INPUTS
        pipe - The pipeline.

    SEE ALSO
        RunFFPipeline(), StopFFGraph()


fastforward.library/UnlinkFFPad           fastforward.library/UnlinkFFPad

    NAME
        UnlinkFFPad - Disconnect a pad from its peer. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        rc = UnlinkFFPad(pad);
        d0               a0

        LONG UnlinkFFPad(struct FFPad *);

    FUNCTION
        Disconnects pad from its currently linked peer (the value
        returned by GetFFPadAttrsA(FFPA_Peer, ...)). Both ends
        return to the unlinked state. Per-link plumbing - message
        ports, buffer pools, signal allocations - is reclaimed.

        Used by editors to detach an element from the data flow
        before disposing or replacing it. May be safely called on
        a pad that is not currently linked.

    INPUTS
        pad - The pad.

    RESULT
        rc - FFERR_NONE on success.

    SEE ALSO
        LinkFFPads(), GetFFElementPad(), GetFFPadAttrsA()


fastforward.library/UnloadFFPlugins       fastforward.library/UnloadFFPlugins

    NAME
        UnloadFFPlugins - Free every registered plugin. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        UnloadFFPlugins();

        VOID UnloadFFPlugins(VOID);

    FUNCTION
        Disposes of every plugin registered with LoadFFPlugins(),
        UnLoadSeg()s each LoadSeg'd binary, and resets the
        registry to its initial state of built-in plugins only.

        Applications normally call this once at shutdown, just
        before FF_CloseLibrary(). UnloadFFPlugins() refuses to
        free plugins that are still in use by an open Movie or
        Graph; close those first.

    SEE ALSO
        LoadFFPlugins(), FindFFPluginA(), NextFFPlugin()


fastforward.library/WaitFFClock           fastforward.library/WaitFFClock

    NAME
        WaitFFClock - Wait until a clock reaches a target time or
                      a signal arrives. (V1)

    SYNOPSIS
        signals = WaitFFClock(clock, time, sigmask);
        d0                    a0     d0    d1

        ULONG WaitFFClock(struct FFClock *, ULONG, ULONG);

    FUNCTION
        Blocks the calling task until either the clock reaches
        time (in its configured time scale) or one of the bits in
        sigmask is signalled. Returns the bitmask of received
        signals so multiplexing on Ctrl-C, IDCMP, MIDI input et
        cetera works as usual:

            while (running) {
                ULONG now = GetFFClockTime(clock);
                ULONG sigs = WaitFFClock(clock,
                                         now + 1,
                                         SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C);
                if (sigs & SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C) break;
                /* schedule next tick of work */
            }

        Sequencers and step-recorders use WaitFFClock() to fire
        events at tempo-quantised boundaries; transport widgets
        use it as the per-tick refresh primitive.

    INPUTS
        clock   - The clock.
        time    - Target time in clock-scale units.
        sigmask - Additional signal bits to observe.

    RESULT
        signals - Bitmask of received signals (zero if WaitFFClock
                  returned because the clock reached time).

    SEE ALSO
        GetFFClockTime(), SetFFClockTime(), StartFFClock(),
        StopFFClock(), exec.library/Wait()
